passages.text: August 28, 2025 10:28 PM GMT
Remain UW post soft underlying F1Q results, with US and global spirits markets still weak, structural headwinds to alcohol in the US, tough macros, and American whiskey oversupply.

Remain Underweight: BF/B closed down \(- 4.9\%\) today (vs the S&P 500 +0.3%) following soft but broadly in line underlying F1Q results, and a headline beat driven by shipment timing. Organic sales increased \(+1\%\) vs the \(- 3.8\%\) Visible Alpha consensus, but included a \(4\%\) benefit from shipment timing, resulting in underlying net sales \(- 3\%\) , only slightly ahead of low expectations. US OSG was \(- 2\%\) including a \(+6\%\) benefit from shipment timing, with US underlying \(- 8\%\) , worse than expected. The timing benefit was driven by shipments into the channel in the US ahead of distributor transitions and some sell- in for Jack Daniel's Blackberry. BF/B maintained FY26 guidance for - LSD sales/Ol declines, acknowledging low visibility, with F1Q shipment timing favorability expected to reverse in F2Q. We remain Underweight, with US and spirits markets still weak, structural headwinds to alcohol consumption in the US, macro challenges, and American whiskey oversupply. Post F1Q, we maintain our FY26/27 estimates, with lower F2Q estimates offsetting F1Q upside, and maintain our \(\) 29\(PT.\)

Headline Beat on Shipment Timing, Underlying Results Broadly In Line: BrownForman reported a headline F1Q revenue/Adjusted EPS beat driven by shipment timing, with underlying results broadly in line. Org sales increased \(+1\%\) vs the \(- 3.8\%\) Visible Alpha consensus, with underlying net sales \(- 3\%\) ex the shipment timing benefit. US OSG was \(- 2\%\) , but US underlying sales declined \(- 8\%\) , with consumer takeaway down \(- 5\%\) and the delta due to disruptions from the distributor transition. Developed International OSG declined \(- 9\%\) with a \(- 1\%\) headwind from distributor inventory changes and underlying \(- 8\%\) . Emerging Markets OSG was \(+25\%\) including a \(+10\%\) benefit from distributor inventory changes, with underlying \(+15\%\) Global Jack Daniels and total American Whiskey depletions both declined \(- 4\%\) . Gross profit beat by \(+2\%\) with a \(+40\) bps GM beat. With operating expenses - 160 bps below consensus (as a \(\%\) of sales), operating income beat by \(9\%\) . Adjusted EPS, excluding the remaining restructuring charge and a related pension settlement, came in \(\) 0.41\(vs the\) \ \(0.39 /\) 0.36 VA/SA consensus.

Management noted that competitive activity in the total distilled spirits has been "fairly rational" to date, with competition most aggressive in tequila, and American whiskey pricing flat for L13W in Nielsen. We continue to see pricing and/ or market share risk for BF/B in American whiskey amid industry oversupply as aging barrels reach maturity. Per US Treasury Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) data, barreled inventories of American whiskey are up \(33\%\) over the last 3 years, and inventories have been roughly flat sequentially since late 2024 despite production cuts by the major producers. declines in wholesale prices for barrels of aged whiskey on the merchant market, as well as increased availability of allocated bourbons on retail shelves at msrp, which are potential harbingers of broader pricing pressure. While we believe that smaller contract whiskey distillers who lack strong brands are most at risk, Brown- Forman is unlikely to be immune to pricing and/or market share pressure from industry oversupply.

FIQ gross margins increased \(+40\) bps y/y, with a \(+240\) bps benefit from acquisitions and divestitures (the absence of the Sonoma- Cutter and Finlandia TSAs and the Korbel termination), partially offset by - 90 bps of higher costs (from inflation and lower production volumes), - 50 bps of lower price/mix (from growth in New Mix RTDs and lower used barrel sales), and - 50 bps from FX. BF/B continues to expect organic gross margins to be broadly flat for the year, with price/mix offsetting inflation, and reported GM expansion due to the divestitures.
Sales in Canada declined nearly \(60\%\) y/y in FIQ with delistings of American brands by many provinces amid the trade/political dispute. Canada represented

\(\sim 1\%\) of sales for BF/B prior to the dispute. BF/B continued to sell non- American brands such as its tequila portfolio in Canada in FIQ. BF/B engaged by recent trade discussions, but guidance assumes the status quo.

Reiterated FY26 Guidance: BFB maintained EY guidance with low visibility due to "headwinds from consumer uncertainty, potential impact from currently unknown tariffs, and lower non- branded sales of used barrels." BFB continues to expect:

- Organic Net Sales: Decline -LSD% vs -2.6/-2.4% VA/SA consensus.- Organic Operating Income: -LSD% decline vs -1.8%/-3.5% VA/SA consensus on a reported basis.- Effective Tax Rate: In the 21-23% range vs 16.5% VA consensus.- Capex: \(125-135M\) vs the \(138.5M / 133.9M\) VA/SA consensus.
